        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>June 14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Morgan</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I really do not know how to thank you enough for your extraordinary kindness in having taken so much trouble for my sons. Your instructions about their route &amp; your splendid supply of introductions will be invaluable to them.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> With hearty thanks | yours very truly obliged | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to Morgan’s providing information and introductions for CD’s sons (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Howard Darwin</ref> and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref> left for a ten-week tour of the United States on 29 July 1871 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7867.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Asa Gray, 16 July [1871]</ref>). Morgan had visited Down on 9 June 1871 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7808.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to L. H. Morgan, 7 June 1871</ref> and n. 1).</note>
        </div>        
            
